// =============================================================================
// security/zk/halo2/mod.vr — Halo2 + KZG10 zero-knowledge proof system
// =============================================================================
// Layer: 3 (cryptography)
// Dependencies: core, core.security.{hash, ecc.bls12_381}
// References:
//  - Bowe, Grigg, Hopwood, "Halo: Recursive Proof Composition without a
//    Trusted Setup" (2019). https://eprint.iacr.org/2019/1021
//  - Halo2 specification: https://zcash.github.io/halo2/
//  - KZG10: Kate, Zaverucha, Goldberg, "Constant-Size Commitments to
//    Polynomials and Their Applications" (2010).
//  - Plonk: Gabizon, Williamson, Ciobotaru, "PLONK: Permutations over
//    Lagrange-bases for Oecumenical Noninteractive arguments of
//    Knowledge" (2019). https://eprint.iacr.org/2019/953
// =============================================================================
//

// Halo2 is a Plonk-style zero-knowledge proof system over the
// BLS12-381 curve, with KZG10 as the polynomial commitment scheme.
// Used by Zcash Sapling/Orchard, Penumbra, Filecoin EVM and many
// recent rollup designs.
//

// # Why Halo2 (vs Groth16, vs Plonk-base, vs STARK)
//

//  * **No per-circuit trusted setup.** A single universal SRS (one
//    ceremony, one product) serves any circuit up to the SRS's
//    capacity. New circuits need *no* ceremony.
//  * **Recursion-friendly.** Halo's accumulator design lets proofs
//    verify other proofs in ~constant time. Useful for cross-shard
//    rollup proofs, recursive zk-VM step traces, infinite-loop
//    incrementally-verifiable computation.
//  * **Custom gates.** Unlike Plonk-base (only addition + multiplication),
//    Halo2 supports arbitrary low-degree gate polynomials — essential
//    for efficient hash circuits (Poseidon, Rescue) and elliptic-curve
//    arithmetic-circuit shaping.
//  * **Lookup tables.** Plonkish lookups (Halo2 §3.5) compress
//    arbitrary table-membership checks into `O(log N)` gates;
//    canonical for range-proofs, byte decomposition, S-box layers.
//

// # Surface
//

// Three logical sub-modules — re-exported here as `halo2.*`:
//

//  * `circuit` — DSL types: Constraint / Region / Column / Selector /
//    Gate / Lookup. The user constructs an immutable circuit
//    description; the prover instantiates witness values into the
//    column layout it specifies.
//  * `prover`  — `prove(circuit, witness, srs) → Proof`.
//  * `verifier`— `verify(circuit_vk, proof, public_inputs) → Bool`.
//  * `srs`     — universal Structured Reference String generation +
//    serialisation. The chain operator runs `setup(k)` once per
//    deployment; the SRS is then content-addressed and reused.
//

// # Why this ships at `Lifecycle.Conditional`
//
// The compile-time-discharged claim "Halo2 verifier is sound under
// AGM + DLog" depends on:
//   1. BLS12-381 stdlib (now landed) — done.
//   2. A universal SRS ceremony — operational concern, not stdlib.
//   3. End-to-end Verum-mechanised soundness proof — out of scope
//      for v0.1; we cite the Halo2 paper via @framework(halo2_2019, ...)
//      as the upstream proof of soundness (`AdmittedWithIou` status
//      in the codegen-attestation framework).
//
// Once items 2-3 land we promote to `Lifecycle.Theorem`.
// =============================================================================

@arch_module(
    foundation: Foundation.ZfcTwoInacc,
    stratum: MsfsStratum.LFnd,
    lifecycle: Lifecycle.Conditional([
        "BLS12-381 stdlib lands (done)",
        "universal-SRS ceremony output committed in chain genesis",
        "Halo2 soundness re-stated in Verum kernel via @framework(halo2_2019, ...)",
    ]),
)
module core.security.zk.halo2;

public module circuit;
public module prover;
public module verifier;
public module srs;

// =============================================================================
// Re-exports — the typical caller imports just `core.security.zk.halo2`
// =============================================================================

public mount .circuit.{
    // Layout primitives
    Column, ColumnType, Selector, Region, Cell,
    // Constraints
    Constraint, Gate, Lookup, Permutation,
    // Circuit container
    Circuit, ConfigureContext, SynthesizeContext,
    // Helpers — generic constraint shapes
    range_constraint, set_membership_constraint, hash_preimage_constraint,
    // Errors
    CircuitError,
};

public mount .prover.{
    Proof, ProvingKey, prove, prove_with_aux, ProverError,
};

public mount .verifier.{
    VerifyingKey, verify, verify_batch, VerifierError,
};

public mount .srs.{
    UniversalSrs, SrsParams, setup, setup_with_entropy, SrsError,
};
